snippet.textDisplay: What a stupid video, using irrelevant movie clips and implying stylistic choices is alien or otherworldly. There are lots out there that scholars and scientists can't explain, but lack of information doesn't make these objects paranormal in any way. Minoan axes, or the labrys as they can be known in English, accompanied storm gods in different cultures around the Mediterranean and Anatolia, or with female goddesses or priestesses in pre-Greek cultures. Never has anyone with credibility implied they were wielded by giants. In depictions, such as on the sarcophagus of Hagia Triada, they served as pillars around an alter. Think of these labryses as religious, architectural decorations, not weapons by titans. C'mon! Erlik is a Siberian underworld god. The gate isn't as famous as this video makes it out to believe. It's just interesting local folklore that isn't interesting enough for study. And the Cthulu tablet looks like a high schooler's art project. The tentacles look nothing more than someone's awful attempt at making tentacles. The tablet would have looked better if they tried to carve in high-relief instead of taking individual rolled pieces of material like clay and flatten them into crooked tentacles.
